  "prompt": "What function do we use in Java in place of cin>> in C++?",
  "response": "In Java, you can use the `Scanner` class for input, which serves a similar purpose to `cin` in C++. Here's how to use it:\n\n1. Import the `Scanner` class:\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n```\n\n2. Create an instance of `Scanner` to read input from the standard input stream (usually the keyboard):\n```java\nScanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n```\n\n3. Use methods of the `Scanner` class to read different types of input. For example, to read an integer, you would use `nextInt()`:\n```java\nint number = scanner.nextInt();\n```\n\nHere\u2019s a complete example demonstrating the process:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class InputExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n        \n        System.out.print(\"Enter an integer: \");\n        int number = scanner.nextInt();\n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + number);\n        \n        scanner.close(); // Remember to close the scanner\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn the above example, `nextInt()` is equivalent to using `cin >>` in C++. If you want to read other types, you can use methods like `nextLine()`, `nextDouble()`, `nextBoolean()`, etc., depending on your needs.",
